The G20 Leaders met in Bali, Indonesia, on 15-16 November 2022 to address global economic challenges. They reaffirmed their commitment to cooperate and tackle the multidimensional crises caused by the Covid-19 pandemic, climate change, and the war in Ukraine. The leaders emphasized the importance of upholding international law, promoting sustainable development, and addressing global food security challenges. They also discussed issues such as energy transitions, climate change mitigation, biodiversity conservation, and the need to strengthen the international financial system. The leaders expressed their commitment to achieving the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), promoting gender equality, and supporting developing countries in their recovery efforts. They also highlighted the importance of digital transformation, education, research and innovation, and cultural preservation. The G20 leaders reaffirmed their commitment to combating corruption, money laundering, and terrorism financing. They welcomed the outcomes of various G20 working groups and ministerial meetings and thanked Indonesia for its presidency. The next G20 Leaders' Summit will be held in India in 2023.